an audio tape played in a courtroom friday 
featured a copilot saying thats a gun following the sounds of 
shots fired aboard a commuter jetliner that crashed in 1987 
killing all 43 people aboard 
jurors heard the pilot and copilot groan loudly after apparent 
gunfire in the final moments preceding the crash of the pacific 
southwest airlines flight blamed on a guntoting former airline 
employee bent on revenge after he was fired for onthejob theft 
david burke 35 of long beach is alleged to have smuggled a 
44caliber magnum aboard flight 1771 on dec 7 1987 by flashing 
his employee badge at a security gate and bypassing metal detectors 
relatives of eight passengers and two crew members are suing 
psa the los angeles department of airports and a security company 
contending they were negligent in allowing burke to board the jet 
bound for san francisco with a loaded gun 
the airline airport agency and ogden allied aviation services 
corp contend burke was solely responsible for the fatal crash 
burke was an employee of usair the parent company of psa until 
he was fired by a man he allegedly shot in the passenger section of 
the plane before he entered the cockpit and fired on the flight 
crew 
julian andrew hayes jr a pilot and former air traffic 
controller testified as an expert witness for the plaintiffs using 
a recording of the cockpit crews conversation with an air traffic 
controller in oakland 
the tape began with the sound of a possible gunshot 
pilot my god 
sound of second shot 
copilot thats a gun 
pilot yeah i know tell em we got a problem 
copilot sending distress signal 
unknown crew member weve got a problem weve had a gun 
fired are they on board the aircraft 
air controller i beg your pardon 
crew member and weve had a gun fired on board the 
aircraft 
air controller ok do you want to go to monterey can you 
make it sir 
sound of door opening 
unknown female hi captain 
pilot what kind of problem 
loud crashing noise 
pilot and copilot ohh loud groan 
tinkle of breaking glass soft banging sound possibly of the 
cockpit door banging shut 
the plane crashed minutes later in central california 
fbi special agent joseph varley told the jury a 44caliber 
pistol with six spent cartridges was found in the wreckage it was 
traced to an oakland man who said he loaned it to burke 
varley said a note in burkes handwriting and addressed to his 
former supervisor was found that read i think its sort of 
ironical we end up like this i asked for some leniency for my 
family well i got none and youll get none 
ronald wecht attorney for the plaintiffs said burke bought 
about 350000 in flight insurance from a terminal vending machine 
before boarding the airliner 
