<TEXT>
most savings and loan associations will have 
to increase the amount of capital they keep in reserve the 
government says 
the increase is required by current regulations that tie the 
capital standards to the industrys annual profitability 
as a result the federal home loan bank board said friday that 
minimum requirements for most savings and loans will rise from the 
current 344 percent of liabilities to 375 percent at the start of 
next year 
the regulations would gradually increase capital requirements to 
6 percent 
the rules however are likely to be superseded by legislation 
under consideration in congress that would overhaul sampl regulations 
and require thrift operators to put more of their own money at risk 
to stay in business 
the tougher capital requirements proposed by president bush as 
part of his sampl bailout package have been the subject of intense 
debate on capitol hill with differences between house and senate 
proposals likely to be ironed out by a joint conference committee 
under the changes announced friday by the bank board sampls in 
the standard group which includes healthy thrifts and covers 
about 80 percent of the industry would see their capital 
requirements rise to 360 percent on july 1 and to 375 percent 
next january 
capital requirements vary case by case for sampls in the lower 
group made up of thrifts experiencing financial difficulty or 
under federal supervision but their required capital would rise 
by 019 percent on july 1 and another 018 percent next january 
