here are facts and figures on polands parliamentary and senate 
elections sunday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
whats at stake of 460 seats in the sejm or parliament 161 
or 35 percent are open to opposition candidates the remaining 
299 are set aside for members of the communist party or its allies 
all the seats are contested except for a national list of 35 
positions for which the communist coalition selected unopposed 
candidates 
there are 1745 candidates nationwide for the 425 contested 
seats 
in the newly created senate all 100 seats are freely contested 
making it the first fully democratically picked legislative chamber 
in the east bloc there are 553 candidates nationwide for those 
seats 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
voting the polls will be open from 6 am to 10 pm there 
will be 22411 polling places in poland and about 205 abroad 
mainly at polish diplomatic posts and construction projects 
there are 27211188 eligible voters according to the 
government voters must be 18 if they live abroad they must 
provide proof of polish citizenship 
voters cast ballots by crossing out all names on the ballot 
except that of the chosen candidate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
victory margin candidates must receive more than half of the 
votes if none does the two candidates receiving the most ballots 
will participate in runoff elections june 18 
the candidates on the national list in the uncontested races 
also must receive more than 50 percent of the votes if they do 
not the seat will not be filled 
