retiring surgeon general c everett koop said 
saturday the us health care system is unfair to millions of 
americans and he called for the appointment of a presidential 
commission to draft a plan for change 
in a commencement address to 2200 graduates of the university 
of massachusetts at boston koop catalogued the ills of the medical 
delivery and insurance system laying particular emphasis on 
inequities 
our current system of health care is not fair its not just 
and its not the morally strong system this country deserves he 
said 
the 72yearold koop who is retiring this year after eight 
years as surgeon general cited estimates that 37 million americans 
about 15 percent of the population have no health insurance 
while millions of others have only partial coverage 
he said health care costs have been rising at two to three times 
the rate of inflation as a whole and public expectations of 
medical care are fast outracing our ability to pay for them 
the former pediatric surgeon also was critical of both doctors 
and hospitals saying he did not foresee the medical profession 
achieving any success in selfregulation he noted that many 
hospitals have tried to cut the number of indigent patients they 
treat 
i say theres something terribly wrong with a system of health 
care that spends more and more money to serve fewer and fewer 
people he said 
koop provided no specific recommendations for reform however 
beyond suggesting the appointment of a presidential commission 
he did not call for national health insurance even though he 
was introduced by sen edward m kennedy dmass a strong 
supporter of that concept 
he also steered clear of the term socialized medicine saying he 
favored a laissezfaire marketplace and a competitive economy 
one of the problems of the current health care system he said is 
that it is distinguished by a lack of competition in price 
quality or service 
we need a presidential commission the bluest of blueribbon 
panels to consider the future of health care in america he said 
koop suggested that the panel include health care professionals 
insurance industry representatives and members of congress 
while the creation of a more equitable health care system will 
be a major task for america koop said it is something we 
need to prove to ourselves and the world if the nation is to 
retain its moral strength 
