for crowded summer beaches and communities up to 10 miles away 
the truth is you cannot evacuate hampton beach and the other 
beaches and protect the people attorney robert backus who has 
represented antiseabrook groups since 1972 told the crowd 
the truth is we dont know what to do with nuclear waste 
backus said the truth is that the plant is uneconomic 
before the weekend at least 300 to 500 people went through 
training sessions on nonviolent civil disobedience clamshell 
spokesman paul gunter said the sessions continued saturday 
on sunday some activists planned to climb fences surrounding 
the 715acre plant site and others planned to sit down outside 
gates some protesters also planned to go to a railroad siding at 
the plant to recreate an august 1976 protest in which 18 people 
were arrested the first group civil disobedience against a us 
nuclear power plant 
earlier in the week superior court judge vincent dunn let the 
town charge the organizers a 300 fee and 3600 bond for an 
assembly permit clamshell members said they couldnt and wouldnt 
pay 
since a town ordinance bars gatherings of more than 25 people 
without a permit the activists said they planned to march to the 
plant on sunday in groups of fewer than 20 
</TEXT>
