<TEXT>
many americans think the current focus on ethics 
is paralyzing the us government but about half said speaker jim 
wright was treated fairly by the house of representatives 
according to a poll released saturday 
fiftyfour percent of the people interviewed said the attention 
to ethics was preventing the government from focusing on the budget 
deficit education crime drugs and the homeless according to the 
poll which will be published in this weeks newsweek magazine 
but 41 percent said it was necessary to restore integrity and 
confidence in government 
on the controversial issue of congressional pay raises 56 
percent of americans oppose any pay increase the poll found 
fifteen percent said congress should get a raise and 26 percent 
said members should get a raise only if they give up speaking fees 
the poll said 
asked to describe congress greatest problem 53 percent said 
members were not dealing with the nations real problems 20 
percent said they were too tied to special interests through 
campaign contributions and 18 percent pointed to the sexual 
misconduct excessive drinking and unethical financial dealings of 
members 
fortynine percent said the house gave fair treatment to wright 
who announced his resignation last week after being cited for 
ethics violations twentyeight percent said he wasnt treated 
fairly and 23 percent said they did not know according to the poll 
although 53 percent of the people surveyed said most or many 
members of congress take unethical advantage of their positions to 
make outside income 47 percent said their own representatives take 
no such an advantage thirtyone percent said they did and 22 
percent did not know 
the poll conducted for newsweek by the gallup organization 
interviewed 750 adults by telephone thursday and friday the margin 
of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points 
