<DOCNO> AP890603-0149 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the germans thought the diminutive horse soldiers 
with oriental features were devils when they first invaded europe 
in the 5th century with attila the hun at their head 
nine centuries later the middle east recoiled in horror as 
another eurasian horde led by tamerlane razed cities and stacked 
human skulls into towering pyramids 
the chinese even built the great wall of china in the 3rd 
century to keep out the havocwreaking warriors 
but scholars say the eurasian nomads were not the simple 
barbarians history often has portrayed them as situated along key 
trade routes linking asia and europe the nomadic tribes had a 
class system and customs and invented saddles the game of polo 
and bowstringed instruments 
they created their own culture in spite of being viewed as 
barbarians by the sedentary population said dr vladimir 
basilov chief curator of the soviet exhibit nomads masters of 
the eurasian steppe which opened june 4 at the denver museum of 
natural history 
we shouldnt think that they just rode with their animals 
dirty and joyful with their food again they created their own 
culture 
the exhibit which covers a 3000year span of the nomadic 
culture represents the largest cultural exchange in the field of 
natural history between the united states and the soviet union 
featuring nearly 1400 artifacts the exhibit began its us 
tour in february at the natural history museum of los angeles 
county it will remain in denver through sept 10 and will make 
its final stop at the smithsonian institution in washington the 
exhibit also has been shown in japan finland and london 
the artifacts were collected from eight museums across the 
soviet union and include some that never have been displayed in the 
soviet union museum officials said 
basilov who has worked on the project for about 10 years said 
the three us sites were chosen because they were large enough to 
accommodate the exhibits size 
from mannequins modeling brilliantly colored clothing to a tiny 
bronze lock molded in the shape of a deer the exhibit provides an 
unusual glimpse into the nomadic culture 
among the artifacts is a fullsize suit of golden armor 
complete with headdress that was uncovered in the tomb of a 
warrior there are examples of weaponry cooking and eating 
utensils carved from wood and gourds and small wooden trunks 
the yurt a rounded tentlike structure with a wool covering to 
keep out the rain provides a look at the nomadic home life 
inside the tent is divided for men and women in the traditional 
setup 
delicate carved jewelry and a silverandgilt saddle arch and 
other ornaments also are in the display 
roaming along the eurasian steppe a grassland area ranging from 
northern china to europe the nomadic tribes thrived from 800 bc 
into the early 20th century some of the wellknown leaders were 
attila the hun and kublai khan and tamerlane descendants of 
genghis khan 
the tribes moved animal herds from pasture to pasture and 
traveled along the silk road a major trade route used to transport 
silk and other goods from china to india and the middle east 
museum officials said the nomads have been credited with helping 
develop economic trade and sharing ideas on religion art and 
technology 
they invented their own dwellings that could be transported 
from one place to another basilov said they thought about the 
possibility to make everything they possess light not heavy not 
breakable so convenient to their way of life 
among their inventions were the trousers saddles and harnesses 
for horses and bowstringed instruments the curator said 
although there still are nomads living in the soviet union and 
parts of mongolia basilov said they have settled into a more 
sedentary lifestyle such as sheepherders moving their flocks 
between permanent dwellings 
but the way of life still has the flavor of their own essence 
of culture some elders that live today remember that in their 
youth they had this way of life he said 
basilov received his doctorate in anthropology from the 
mikloukhomaclay institute of ethnography in moscow part of the 
academy of sciences of the soviet union he has held several 
positions including senior researcher and scientific secretary at 
the institute currently he heads the institutes department of 
central asian and kazakhstan research 
he believes the exhibit is unique because its message is that 
the nomads were not just barbaric tribes 
although basilov has worked on the project for more than a 
decade it still fascinates him the more you work the more 
interest you have in different fields of this very interesting 
culture 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

